III. Data and EDA

Source

  • Multivariate Normal Data

Variable

  • Simple
    • Four group
    • N = 400
    • \(x_1\), \(x_2\), \(x_3\), \(x_4\)
    • First group mean is (1, 2, 3, 4)
    • Second group mean is (5, 6, 7, 8)
    • Third group mean is (9, 10, 11, 12)
    • Fourth group mean is (13, 14, 15, 16)
  • Common
    • Four group
    • N = 400
    • \(x_1\), \(x_2\), \(x_3\), \(x_4\)
    • First group mean is (1, 2, 3, 5)
    • Second group mean is (2, 4, 6, 9)
    • Third group mean is (10, 11, 12, 13)
    • Fourth group mean is (13, 11.5, 10.5, 15)
  • Difficulty
    • Four group
    • N = 400
    • \(x_1\), \(x_2\), \(x_3\) , \(x_4\)
    • First group mean is (1, 2, 5, 7)
    • Second group mean is (0.5, 1.5, 4.5, 6.5)
    • Third group mean is (0.25, 0.75, 2.25, 3.25)
    • Fourth group mean is (0.125, 0.375, 1.125, 1.625)
  • Unbalance
    • Four group
    • \(x_1\), \(x_2\), \(x_3\), \(x_4\)
    • First group N is 100
    • Second group N is 100
    • Third group N is 1000
    • Fourth group N is 500
    • First group mean is (1, 2, 3, 4)
    • Second group mean is (5, 6, 7, 8)
    • Third group mean is (10, 12, 14, 16)
    • Fourth group mean is (11, 13, 15, 17)

IV. Model

Using K-Fold Cross-Validation divide the data into five part

Simple

easy.num <- kfcv(easy, seed=1116, k = 5)

CART

success <-0

for(i in 1:5){
  
  easy.train <- easy[-easy.num[[i]],]
  easy.test <- easy[easy.num[[i]],]
  
  easy.tree <- rpart(type ~., data = easy.train)

  tree.test.pred <- predict(easy.tree, newdata = easy.test, type="class")
  tree.test.table <- table(easy.test$type, tree.test.pred, dnn = c("actual", "predict"))
  correct.tree.test <- sum(diag(tree.test.table))
  correct.tree.test
  

  success <- success + correct.tree.test
  
}

Confusion Matrix

knitr::kable(tree.test.table,row.names = TRUE)
1 2 3 4
1 24 0 0 0
2 0 18 0 0
3 0 0 18 0
4 0 0 1 19

Testing data accuracy

(success/400)*100
## [1] 97.5

Random Forest

success <-0

for(i in 1:5){
  
  easy.train <- easy[-easy.num[[i]],]
  easy.test <- easy[easy.num[[i]],]
  
  easy.rf <- randomForest(type~., data = easy.train, ntree=500)
  rf.test.pred <- predict(easy.rf, newdata = easy.test)
  rf.test.table <- table(easy.test$type, rf.test.pred, dnn = c("actual", "pred"))
  correct.rf.test <- sum(diag(rf.test.table))
  correct.rf.test
  
  success <- success + correct.rf.test
  
}
